Where was the great orator? Was this the man who might have been expected to lift the spirits of a stricken community with a spellbinding statement like Franklin Roosevelt’s “We have nothing to fear but fear itself”, or even an unguarded display of genuine feeling as Ronald Reagan or Bill Clinton would have produced? Was he lost without a script – as he seemed to be in that startling first debate with Mitt Romney? Or, indeed, in the second and third debates too – where again, he went small instead of big. The great themes that should have dominated his message and the entire campaign, considering that the United States is now in the throes of the worst economic downturn since the Great Depression, were lost in a morass of incomprehensible data and petulant retorts: technical minutiae and obscure debating points were thrown up like flak to conceal – what? The absence of any remaining big idea? Or the sense that his presidency, having exhausted all its political energy over Obamacare, had lost its way? Or that he is out of his depth on the economy?
But if Obama loses the White House, everyone – absolutely everyone – will attribute that fact to the fatal first presidential debate. And that will be largely right, not just because the President performed badly but because the public expectation of Mitt Romney was so dramatically contravened. Having been traduced and travestied by an Obama-worshipping mass media, Mr Romney simply became himself: reasonable, intelligent, obviously pleasant and impressively commanding of the argument. The electorate was not just bowled over with surprise, it was outraged by the misrepresentation of this man who had been depicted as half-monster, half-buffoon. American voters learnt an important truth not only about Mr Romney, but also about the systematic bias of the media – which would not regain the public trust again, and thus became worse than useless as cheerleader for the President. As one pundit put it, the media had “loved Obama to death”.
Like everybody with any sense, I am not going to make a prediction of the outcome. This one is truly too close to call. But I have two observations which may or may not prove pertinent. The first is that there could be a significant number of people intending to vote for Romney who, bullied by the liberal media, are not saying so to the opinion pollsters. And the second: I am sure that many Americans of good conscience voted for Obama in 2008 because they wished to exorcise the country’s hideous racial history. But having proved with that election that America is no longer a nation of bigots, they do not have to do it again. If they reject him now, they will be doing so on the basis of his record in office, not his race. He will have been judged as any president – of any colour – would have been. So if Mr Obama loses, it will not be the end of post-racial politics. It will be the beginning.
